# 6-DoF Simulation Final Report
## 1. System Architecture

The current iteration of the Icarus simulator has transitioned from a basic PID-controlled plant to a full closed-loop system incorporating multi-sensor fusion and cascaded control logic. The simulation environment models nonlinear 3D quadcopter dynamics, including thrust nonlinearities, motor lag, and Euler-angle attitude kinematics.
## 2. State Estimation Strategy

To mitigate the impact of high-frequency sensor noise on control stability, a bifurcated estimation architecture was implemented:

    Translational Estimation (6-State KF): A Kalman Filter was developed to estimate the translational state vector x=[x,y,z,vx​,vy​,vz​]T. By fusing simulated IMU accelerations with low-frequency GPS and Altimeter measurements, the filter provides a smooth, low-latency estimate of position and velocity. This has successfully resolved previous issues regarding divergent oscillations during long-distance waypoint transitions.

    Attitude Estimation (Complementary Filter): For orientation, a Complementary Filter fuses gyroscope integration (high-frequency) with accelerometer-based tilt sensing (low-frequency). This maintains a stable estimate of the vehicle's roll and pitch without the drift associated with raw integration or the computational cost of a full EKF.

## 3. Control Performance & Verification

The guidance and control pipeline utilizes a cascaded PID architecture. The outer loop manages position tracking by generating target Euler angles and thrust setpoints, which are then passed to a high-rate inner loop for attitude and rate control.

### Key Performance Metrics:

    Steady-State Error: The system demonstrates high precision in trajectory tracking, with a verified steady-state position error of <8 cm during waypoint hovering.

    Transient Response: Step-response analysis of 3-meter multi-axis maneuvers shows a settling time of <3 seconds.

    Stability: The inclusion of derivative filtering and integral anti-windup has effectively dampened the "growing oscillations" observed in earlier, unfiltered versions of the controller.

## 4. Path Forward

The verified Python dynamics and GNC logic are currently being ported to an embedded C++ architecture.

    Objective: Implement an asynchronous flight control loop using MAVSDK.

    Testing: Development of a Hardware-in-the-Loop (HIL) environment to bridge the gap between the 6-DoF simulation and the physical CUAV V5 Nano flight controller via a Raspberry Pi companion computer.

## 5. LQR vs PID Attitude Control - Comparative Results

The inner attitude PID loop was replaced with a Linear Quadratic Regulator (LQR) 
derived from the linearised hover dynamics. The attitude plant was linearised as a 
decoupled set of double integrators at hover, yielding a 6-state system 
[φ, θ, ψ, p, q, r] with torque inputs [τ_φ, τ_θ, τ_ψ]. Q and R matrices were 
initialised using Bryson's rule and the optimal gain matrix K was computed by 
solving the Continuous Algebraic Riccati Equation (CARE) via scipy.

The outer position loop remained as a PD controller, retaining the cascade 
architecture. Settling times and final position error were measured across a 
5-waypoint mission:

| Waypoint | PID Settle | LQR Settle |
|----------|------------|------------|
| WP0      | 2.2s       | 1.7s       |
| WP1      | 4.8s       | 3.8s       |
| WP2      | 7.1s       | 6.1s       |
| WP3      | 9.6s       | 8.3s       |
| WP4      | 12.2s      | 10.5s      |
| Final error | 6.4cm   | 3.9cm      |

LQR achieved 14-23% faster settling across all waypoints and a 39% reduction in 
final position error. The improvement is attributed to LQR's systematic optimal 
gain selection, which provides better-damped rate response than the hand-tuned PD 
attitude controller.

A key finding during tuning was that the cascade architecture imposes a bandwidth 
separation constraint — the outer position loop natural frequency must remain well 
below the inner attitude loop to avoid exciting sustained oscillations. This limits 
outer loop aggressiveness regardless of inner loop quality. Full-state LQR across 
all 12 states is identified as the natural next step, eliminating the cascade 
constraint entirely.

## 6. Full-State LQR — 12-State Controller

### Architecture
The cascade architecture (outer position PID + inner attitude LQR) was replaced 
with a single full-state LQR controller operating on the complete 12-state vector 
[x, y, z, vx, vy, vz, φ, θ, ψ, p, q, r] with inputs [T, τ_φ, τ_θ, τ_ψ].

The linearised plant at hover captures position-attitude coupling:
- vx_ddot = |g|·θ  (forward acceleration via pitch)
- vy_ddot = -|g|·φ (lateral acceleration via roll)
- vz_ddot = δT/m   (altitude via thrust perturbation)

These coupling terms appear directly in the A matrix, allowing the optimizer to 
account for the full translational-rotational interaction rather than treating 
the two loops as independent. Q and R matrices were initialised via Bryson's rule 
across all 12 states and 4 inputs. The gain matrix K was computed by solving the 
CARE via scipy.

### Three-Way Performance Comparison

| Metric          | PID    | Cascade LQR | Full-State LQR |
|-----------------|--------|-------------|----------------|
| WP0 settle      | 2.2s   | 1.7s        | 1.2s           |
| WP1 settle      | 4.8s   | 3.8s        | 3.1s           |
| WP2 settle      | 7.1s   | 6.1s        | 4.8s           |
| WP3 settle      | 9.6s   | 8.3s        | 6.6s           |
| WP4 settle      | 12.2s  | 10.5s       | 8.3s           |
| Mission time    | 12.2s  | 10.5s       | 8.3s           |
| Final error     | 6.4cm  | 3.9cm       | 7.8cm          |

Full-state LQR completes the mission 32% faster than PID and 21% faster than 
cascade LQR. Each waypoint settles approximately 30% faster than the cascade 
architecture.

### Key Finding
The cascade architecture imposes a hard bandwidth separation constraint — the 
outer position loop natural frequency must stay well below the inner attitude 
loop to avoid sustained oscillations. This limits outer loop aggressiveness 
regardless of inner loop quality. Full-state LQR eliminates this constraint 
entirely by jointly optimizing position and attitude in a single cost function, 
allowing the optimizer to determine the correct bandwidth tradeoff automatically.

### Tradeoffs
Peak attitude angles increased from ±16° (cascade LQR) to ±22° (full-state LQR) 
during 3-meter step maneuvers, reflecting more aggressive position tracking. 
Thrust perturbations are larger during braking transitions. Both are within 
acceptable bounds and damp out cleanly between waypoints.